15:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Bitget uses traditional 8-hour funding intervals with standard premium/discount calculations based on perpetual-spot price divergence. Drift implements hourly funding on Solana using its vAMM model, allowing for more frequent rate adjustments and potentially smoother convergence. Drift's shorter intervals can capture micro-movements but may increase transaction costs for position holders. Bitget's longer intervals provide more predictable funding costs but may allow larger price divergences to persist."}]]}]
16:["$","$L17",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which exchange has better funding rate arbitrage opportunities?","answer":"Drift's 1-hour funding intervals provide more frequent arbitrage windows compared to Bitget's 8-hour cycles. However, Bitget's higher liquidity may offer better execution for larger positions."},{"question":"How do transaction costs affect funding arbitrage profits?","answer":"Drift benefits from Solana's low transaction costs but charges similar trading fees. Bitget's higher taker fees (0.06% vs 0.05%) can impact profitability on frequent rebalancing strategies."},{"question":"Which platform is better for automated funding strategies?","answer":"Drift's on-chain nature allows for programmable strategies via smart contracts, while Bitget offers traditional API access with copy trading features for automated execution."},{"question":"How does liquidity affect funding rate stability?","answer":"Bitget typically maintains deeper order books providing more stable funding rates. Drift's vAMM model can experience higher volatility in funding rates during low liquidity periods."}]}]
